In standard GR, it’s fundamental: spacetime is dynamical, curved by energy. In PUH v25, the substrate is a discrete lattice with fixed geometry — no fundamental diffeomorphism invariance. However, in the long-wavelength continuum limit, an effective metric emerges from refractive index variations n(x). Simple picture: •  Uniform substrate → n=1 → flat Minkowski metric η_μν. •  Mass knots → local n(r)>1 gradients → effective optical metric g_μν = n² η_μν (light cones tilt). •  Coordinate transformations on the effective metric are preserved → general covariance emerges as an approximate symmetry of low-energy physics.
